# Backend Conventions

## Route Structure
Every resource follows this pattern:
- `GET /api/<resource>` — public, `isActive: true` only, limited `select`
- `GET /api/admin/<resource>` — `authMiddleware`, returns all records
- `POST /api/<resource>` — `authMiddleware` + `upload.single('file')`, create
- `PUT /api/<resource>/:id` — `authMiddleware` + optional file, update
- `PATCH /api/<resource>/:id/toggle` — `authMiddleware`, flip `isActive`
- `DELETE /api/<resource>/:id` — `authMiddleware`, delete S3 file + DB row

## S3 Uploads
- Always wrap `uploadToS3()` in try/catch — log the error but don't fail the request.
- If photo upload fails, save the record without the photo (`photoUrl` = null).

```typescript
// ✅ Correct
let photoUrl: string | undefined;
if (req.file) {
  try {
    const result = await uploadToS3(req.file, 'folder');
    photoUrl = result.s3Url;
  } catch (err) {
    console.error('S3 upload failed:', err);
  }
}
```

## Error Responses
- Always return `{ error: "description" }` with the appropriate HTTP status.
- Log server errors with `console.error` before returning 500.
- Never expose stack traces or internal details to the client.

## Prisma
- Use `lib/prisma.ts` singleton — never create new instances.
- New models must include: `id` (uuid), `isActive` (default true), `createdAt`, `updatedAt`.
- Run `npx prisma db push` and `npx prisma generate` after schema changes.
